# E320 FIFO Spectrogram Toolkit
A host-side SDR visualization toolkit for the Ettus E320.
This project allows you to view **live RF spectrum and waterfall data** from an E320 on a separate host machine using a FIFO stream over SSH. It also supports **synthetic signal generation** for GUI testing without any RF hardware activity.
---
# Overview
Instead of controlling the E320 directly from the host with UHD, the radio captures IQ samples locally and streams them to the host.
This architecture avoids host/UHD version mismatch issues and keeps the radio-side capture path simple and reliable.
```text
E320 RX Capture (local UHD)
        ↓
SSH stdout stream
        ↓
Host FIFO (/tmp/e320_iq.pipe)
        ↓
GNU Radio + PyQt GUI
        ↓
Spectrum + Waterfall

⸻

Included Components

1. waterfall_sigmf.py

Primary host-side GUI application.

Features:

* Reads interleaved int16 IQ samples from a FIFO
* Converts to complex baseband IQ
* Live FFT spectrum display
* Live waterfall display
* Dark professional SDR-style interface
* Optional rolling SigMF recording
* Metadata header (frequency, gain, source, status)

⸻

2. launch_e320_spectrogram.sh

One-command launcher.

Automates:

* FIFO creation
* E320 SSH receive stream
* GUI startup
* cleanup on exit

⸻

3. Synthetic Signal Generator

Host-side FIFO generator used to simulate RF scenes without using the E320.

Useful for:

* GUI development
* waterfall tuning
* FFT testing
* occupied-band simulation
* blocker/interference simulation

⸻

Installation Requirements

Host machine:

* Python 3
* GNU Radio
* PyQt5
* NumPy
* SigMF Python package (optional if recording enabled)
* SSH access to E320

⸻

Live E320 Mode

Launch Everything Automatically

./launch_e320_spectrogram.sh \
  --freq 102700000 \
  --rate 1000000 \
  --gain 40 \
  --ant RX2

This will:

1. Create FIFO:

/tmp/e320_iq.pipe

2. Start E320 receive stream
3. Launch GUI

⸻

Disable SigMF Recording

./launch_e320_spectrogram.sh \
  --freq 102700000 \
  --rate 1000000 \
  --gain 40 \
  --no-sigmf

⸻

Manual GUI Launch

If IQ data is already flowing into the FIFO:

python3 waterfall_sigmf.py \
  --fifo /tmp/e320_iq.pipe \
  --samp-rate 1000000 \
  --center-freq 102700000

Disable recording:

python3 waterfall_sigmf.py \
  --fifo /tmp/e320_iq.pipe \
  --samp-rate 1000000 \
  --center-freq 102700000 \
  --no-sigmf

⸻

Synthetic RF Scene Mode

No E320 required.

Creates a realistic occupied band from:

102.600 MHz to 102.800 MHz

when centered at:

102.700 MHz

Result:

* soft band edges
* fading energy
* realistic texture
* waterfall movement

⸻

Start Synthetic Generator

rm -f /tmp/e320_iq.pipe
mkfifo /tmp/e320_iq.pipe
python3 synthetic_blocker.py > /tmp/e320_iq.pipe

Then launch GUI:

python3 waterfall_sigmf.py \
  --fifo /tmp/e320_iq.pipe \
  --samp-rate 1000000 \
  --center-freq 102700000 \
  --no-sigmf

⸻

Signal Flow Details

Live E320 Stream

Internally the launcher runs:

ssh root@192.168.10.2 '/usr/lib/uhd/examples/rx_samples_to_file \
  --args "addr=127.0.0.1" \
  --ant RX2 \
  --file /dev/stdout \
  --type short \
  --rate 1000000 \
  --freq 102700000 \
  --gain 40 \
  --nsamps 0'

This outputs:

int16 I,Q,int16 I,Q,int16 I,Q...

which the GUI converts to complex float samples.

⸻

Frequency Mapping

If GUI center frequency is:

102.700 MHz

Then:

Displayed Frequency	Relative Offset
102.600 MHz	-100 kHz
102.700 MHz	0
102.800 MHz	+100 kHz

⸻

SigMF Recording

When enabled, the GUI writes rolling capture files:

sigmf_YYYYMMDDTHHMMSSZ_0000.sigmf-data
sigmf_YYYYMMDDTHHMMSSZ_0000.sigmf-meta

Each chunk duration is configurable:

--chunk-seconds 5

Disable completely:

--no-sigmf

